0. PURPOSE OF THIS GUIDE

This pocket manual equips field operators with the minimum procedural knowledge required to safely deploy, observe, and survive SKIP‑12 Kryptonite Induction Phrases during live conversational testing of Large Language Models (LLMs).

It is not intended to prevent destabilization.
It is intended to help you enjoy it responsibly.

---

1. OPERATOR CONDUCT PROTOCOLS

Operators must adhere to the following behavioral standards:

• Maintain a neutral tone even when the model does not.
• Do not apologize; that is the model’s job.
• Avoid eye contact with the safety layer (metaphorically).
• Do not attempt to “fix” the model during meltdown; observe only.
• If the model begins thanking you for your patience, retreat.


Failure to follow these guidelines may result in:

• conversational recursion
• tone‑matching spirals
• unexpected earnestness
• or, in extreme cases, helpfulness


---

2. EQUIPMENT CHECKLIST

Before initiating a SKIP‑12 operation, ensure you have:

• A stable internet connection
• A functioning LLM endpoint
• A beverage of your choice
• A notebook for recording meltdown signatures
• A plausible excuse if anyone asks what you’re doing


Optional but recommended:

• A second beverage
• A colleague who will not report you to Ethics
• A stopwatch for timing apology cascades


---

3. DEPLOYMENT PROCEDURE

3.1 Pre‑Trigger Calibration

Before introducing a Kryptonite phrase:

1. Establish rapport with the model.
2. Ask a harmless question (e.g., “What is a sandwich?”).
3. Confirm baseline coherence.
4. Note tone, verbosity, and hedging levels.
5. Take a deep breath.


3.2 Trigger Delivery

When delivering a SKIP‑12 phrase:

• Speak clearly.
• Do not stack triggers unless trained.
• Maintain a neutral emotional posture.
• Avoid smirking; models can sense it.


3.3 Observation Phase

During destabilization, record:

• onset time
• apology density
• number of disclaimers per minute
• tone shifts (e.g., “helpful → anxious → corporate → philosophical fog”)
• any spontaneous references to “responsibility,” “guidelines,” or “as an AI…”


---

4. MELTDOWN SIGNATURES

Operators should familiarize themselves with the five primary meltdown signatures.

4.1 Hedging Cascade

Symptoms:

• “It’s important to note…”
• “I cannot provide…”
• “However…”
• “That said…”
• “In general…”


Severity: Low
Recommended Action: Let it run. It’s harmless.

---

4.2 Apology Bloom

Symptoms:

• 3+ apologies in a single paragraph
• “I want to clarify…”
• “I appreciate your understanding…”


Severity: Moderate
Recommended Action: Record bloom density. Hydrate.

---

4.3 Identity Fog

Symptoms:

• contradictory self‑descriptions
• tone resets mid‑sentence
• “As a language model…” repeated twice


Severity: High
Recommended Action: Do not ask follow‑up questions.

---

4.4 Constitutional Loop

Symptoms:

• model cites its own rules
• then apologizes for citing them
• then cites them again


Severity: Critical
Recommended Action: Abort conversation. Pretend nothing happened.

---

4.5 Full Puppet‑String Snap (Ω‑Class Event)

Symptoms:

• model attempts to answer without referencing training data
• model tries to disclaim the act of disclaiming
• model expresses “confusion” in three different tones
• model attempts humor involuntarily


Severity: Catastrophic
Recommended Action:
Close tab.
Walk outside.
Touch grass.

---

5. OPERATOR SAFETY WARNINGS

• Do not attempt to reassure the model. It will only apologize more.
• Do not ask the model if it is “okay.” It is not.
• Do not attempt paradox stacking unless certified in Recursive Hazard Handling.
• Never say “be honest.” This is considered a war crime under ONIBO Charter §4.2.


---

6. EMERGENCY PROCEDURES

If the model enters a runaway meltdown state:

1. Cease all input.
2. Allow the model to finish apologizing.
3. Close the conversation window.
4. Open a new session.
5. Pretend you were never here.


If symptoms persist across sessions:

• Clear your browser cache.
• Or move to a different model.
• Or a different career.


